---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="About ByteLite | The HeartStrings Discovery"
  description="How ByteLite revolutionary compression was discovered while building an AI dating app in 2024."
>
  <div class="bg-dark-navy text-white">
    <!-- Hero Section -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-gradient-to-br from-deep-space to-dark-navy">
      <div class="container mx-auto px-6">
        <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto text-center">
          <h1 class="text-5xl font-bold mb-6">The HeartStrings Discovery</h1>
          <p class="text-xl text-gray-300 mb-8">
            How a quest to build a smarter dating app accidentally discovered
            the most powerful compression algorithm ever created
          </p>
          <div class="inline-flex items-center bg-electric-cyan/10 border border-electric-cyan/30 rounded-full px-6 py-2">
            <span class="text-electric-cyan font-mono">US Patent 63/807,027</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Origin Story -->
    <section class="py-20">
      <div class="container mx-auto px-6">
        <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-electric-cyan mb-8">The Origin Story</h2>

          <div class="prose prose-lg text-gray-300 space-y-6">
            <p class="text-xl">
              ByteLite was born out of necessity?not in a lab, but in the trenches of real-world innovation. 
              In early 2024, Tash Broadwater began building a dating app called <em>HeartStrings</em>, intended 
              to feature a smart AI wingman capable of deeply personalized matchmaking. The AI needed to 
              understand more from less?to intuit character and compatibility from limited input.
            </p>

            <p>
              But the available AI models hit a wall. Their appetite for data and hardware made them 
              inaccessible to independent developers. That bottleneck sparked a new question:
            </p>

            <blockquote class="text-xl text-electric-cyan font-semibold border-l-4 border-electric-cyan pl-6">
              "What if the problem isn't the AI?but the way we represent information?"
            </blockquote>

            <p>
              This led to a radical shift: convert a hardware problem into a software solution by 
              compressing data so efficiently that smaller models could gain deeper insights with fewer resources.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- The Discovery -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-deep-space/30">
      <div class="container mx-auto px-6">
        <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-quantum-pink mb-8">The Discovery</h2>

          <div class="prose prose-lg text-gray-300 space-y-6">
            <p>
              While developing preprocessing methods to enable lean AI inference, Tash stumbled upon 
              something much bigger?a method of perfectly lossless, recursive compression. By fusing 
              <strong>Szudzik pairing functions</strong> with <strong>adaptive multi-layered dictionaries</strong>, 
              data could be represented far more efficiently than previously thought possible.
            </p>

            <p>
              Each round of compression reduced the dataset further, halving its size recursively, 
              until the entropy floor was reached. Standard compressors failed at this point. 
              ByteLite didn't. It kept going?reliably.
            </p>

            <p class="text-xl font-bold text-electric-cyan">
              In late 2024, a 1GB dataset was compressed down to just 15 bytes using this recursive architecture.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- The Algorithm -->
    <section class="py-20">
      <div class="container mx-auto px-6">
        <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-electric-cyan mb-8">The Algorithm</h2>

          <p class="text-gray-300 mb-6">
            ByteLite's <strong>Dynamic Algorithmic Compression</strong> system uses:
          </p>

          <div class="space-y-3 text-gray-300">
            <p>- Recursive Szudzik pairing of bit-aligned structures</p>
            <p>- Segmented Domain Dictionary (SDD) encoding with six layers</p>
            <p>- Hardcoded, pop-count-sorted dictionaries</p>
            <p>- Padding mechanisms to preserve reversibility</p>
            <p>- Multithreaded system profilers to optimize for underlying hardware</p>
          </div>

          <p class="text-gray-300 mt-6">
            The algorithm isn't just efficient?it's mathematically elegant, consistent, and shockingly scalable.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Milestones -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-deep-space/30">
      <div class="container mx-auto px-6">
        <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-quantum-pink mb-8">Milestones</h2>

          <div class="space-y-6">
            <div class="border-l-4 border-electric-cyan pl-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-electric-cyan">2024 Q3</h3>
              <p class="text-gray-300">First algorithm prototype, using manual pairing and bit-string testing</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="border-l-4 border-quantum-pink pl-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-quantum-pink">2024 Q4</h3>
              <p class="text-gray-300">1GB to 15 byte test successful; algorithm validated against enwik9</p>
            </div>

            <div class="border-l-4 border-electric-cyan pl-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-electric-cyan">2025 Q1</h3>
              <p class="text-gray-300">Provisional patent filed (USPTO 63/807,027)</p>
            </div>

            <div class="border-l-4 border-quantum-pink pl-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-quantum-pink">2025 Q2</h3>
              <p class="text-gray-300">Independent validation completed; internal benchmarks published</p>
            </div>

            <div class="border-l-4 border-electric-cyan pl-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-electric-cyan">2025 Q3</h3>
              <p class="text-gray-300">Enterprise licensing opened; SBIR & xTechSearch submissions made</p>
            </div>

            <div class="border-l-4 border-quantum-pink pl-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-quantum-pink">2025 Q4</h3>
              <p class="text-gray-300">ByteLite prepares for Hutter Prize & NSF full proposal</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Philosophy -->
    <section class="py-20">
      <div class="container mx-auto px-6">
        <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-electric-cyan mb-8">Philosophy and Brand</h2>

          <p class="text-gray-300 mb-6">
            ByteLite is more than an algorithm?it's a philosophy of efficient intelligence. 
            Its visual identity reflects this:
          </p>

          <div class="space-y-4 text-gray-300">
            <p>- The <strong class="text-green-400">green leaf</strong> symbolizes eco-conscious computation: doing more with less.</p>
            <p>- The <strong class="text-blue-400">blue wave</strong> stands for recursive depth: learning, compressing, and evolving.</p>
            <p>- The <strong class="text-electric-cyan">infinity symbol</strong> represents limitless potential through transformation.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Founder Bio -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-deep-space/30">
      <div class="container mx-auto px-6">
        <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-quantum-pink mb-8">Founder Bio ? Tash Broadwater</h2>

          <p class="text-gray-300 text-lg">
            Tash is a compression researcher and software engineer with over 15 years of experience 
            optimizing data systems for speed and efficiency. A Montana native with blue-collar grit 
            and academic curiosity, Tash specializes in algorithmic design, bit-level logic, and AI 
            systems that work <em>on the edge</em>, not just the cloud.
          </p>

          <p class="text-gray-300 text-lg mt-6">
            When traditional solutions fail, Tash builds new ones from scratch?and ByteLite is the 
            result of that ethos.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>
</Layout>
